    "remarks": {
      "sha256": "6370178ae96dc007455c8a3f7452a426419b69001301f0b2fe63e4a8765eed53",
      "source_region": "div.problem-additional-text",
      "text": "Erd\\H{o}s also conjectured (see [364]) that there are no triples of powerful numbers of the shape $n,n+1,n+2$."
    },
    "statement": {
      "sha256": "02cdc1e3f80aabd59ccd1fe980aee10b26ec8a9e04618346a5a71b5652363d9a",
      "source_region": "div#content",
      "text": "Let $A=\\{n_1<n_2<\\cdots\\}$ be the sequence of powerful numbers (if $p\\mid n$ then $p^2\\mid n$).\n\nAre there only finitely many three-term progressions of consecutive terms $n_k,n_{k+1},n_{k+2}$?"
    }
  },
